Sure! Below is the content formatted as an HTML form that prompts the user for their social security number. This form includes placeholders and labels to make it clear what information is being requested.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Social Security Number Verification</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            border-radius: 5px;
            max-width: 600px;
            margin: auto;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            color: #333;
        }
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-top: 10px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        input[type="text"], input[type="password"] {
            width: calc(100% - 22px);
            padding: 10px;
            margin-top: 5px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        button {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 10px;
            margin-top: 20px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Verify Your Social Security Number</h1>

<form action="#" method="post">
    <label for="ssn">Enter Your Social Security Number:</label>
    <input type="text" id="ssn" name="ssn" placeholder="####-##-####" pattern="\d{3}-\d{2}-\d{4}" required>

    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure**:
   - The `<!DOCTYPE html>` declaration defines the document type.
   - The `<html>` element contains the entire HTML document.
   - The `<head>` section includes metadata and styles.
   - The `<body>` section contains the main content of the page.

2. **Styling**:
   - Basic CSS is included to style the form, making it visually appealing and user-friendly.
   - The form is centered and has a consistent look.

3. **Form Elements**:
   - A `<h1>` tag for the title.
   - A `<label>` for the social security number field.
   - An `<input>` field for entering the social security number, with a pattern attribute to ensure the correct format.
   - A `<button>` to submit the form.

This HTML form will prompt the user to enter their social security number and submit it. The pattern attribute ensures that the input follows the correct format (####-##-####).

